8","Chrishall, Essex, England":"Chrishall, Essex, England","Mary Magdalene-Cobham, Kent, England, Great Britain":"Cobham, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Cobham, Kent, England":"Cobham, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cobham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of at least three places in southern England called Cobham, in Kent, Surrey, and Sussex."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":40,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Cobham was born about 1342, in Cobham, Kent, England, her father, Sir John Cobham, was 28 and her mother, Margaret Courtenay the elder, was 16. She married John de la Pole about 1362. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died before 1394, in Chrishall, Essex, England, and was buried in Cobham, Kent, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1342–before 1394":"umbes 1342–enne 1394","1342–1394":"1342–1394","1341–1389":"1341–1389","1355–1434":"1355–1434","1316–1408":"1316–1408","1328–1395":"1328–1395","1341":"1341","September 1389":"september 1389","1395":"1395","13 January 1434":"13. jaanuar 1434","1394":"1394","1382":"1382","1316":"1316","1434":"1434","Abt 1355":"umbes 1355","1389":"1389","1355":"1355","1342":"1342","before 1394":"enne 1394","about 1332":"umbes 1332","1408":"1408","about 1342":"umbes 1342","about 1362":"umbes 1362","1328":"1328","Chrishall, Essex, England":"Chrishall, Essex, England","Mary Magdalene-Cobham, Kent, England, Great Britain":"Cobham, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cobham, Kent, England":"Cobham, Kent, England"},"fi":{"about 1342–before 1394":"noin 1342–ennen vuotta 1394","1342–1394":"1342–1394","1341–1389":"1341–1389","1355–1434":"1355–1434","1316–1408":"1316–1408","1328–1395":"1328–1395","1341":"1341","September 1389":"syyskuu 1389","1395":"1395","13 January 1434":"13. tammikuuta 1434","1394":"1394","1382":"1382","1316":"1316","1434":"14